	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Kingston Jamaica</placeName></p>
				<p rend="align(right)"><date>Jany. 4Th 5623&#61;1863</date></p>
				<p>High Esteeme<del>n</del>d</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Revd. &#38; Dear Sir&#33;</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">You really must <del>in</del> with your<lb/> usual kind feeling&#44; pardon my not having addressed<lb/> you on this&#44; as our mutual and esteemed friend <persName>Mr. Nathan</persName><lb/> can assure you that since my arrival here&#44; I have<lb/> had my time fully occupied with public as well as<lb/> private duties.  I need not tell you of my changing<lb/> appointments&#44; as you are already aware of the fact&#59;<lb/> therefore&#44; suffice it for me to inform you&#44; that my<lb/> <del>cause</del> reason for so doing was&#44; that the situation here offered to<lb/> me&#44; was far more beneficial than the one I held in<lb/> <placeName>Saint Thomas</placeName>.  News I have not any to write&#8212;<lb/> you have an excellent and worthy agent here in <persName>Mr.<lb/> Nathan</persName>&#44; to whom I have just handed the name of<lb/> a new subscriber to the &#8220;Occident&#8221;&#8212; As my subscription<lb/> has formerly been sent through <persName>Mr. Piza</persName> of <placeName>St. Thomas</placeName>&#44;<lb/> will you kindly acquaint me as to the date of its<lb/> becoming due&#63;  And&#44; I presume that you will now<lb/> send my numbers through <persName>Mr. N.</persName> as I received the<lb/> are forwarded by last mail.  I read the abusive<lb/> remarks of that scurrilous sheer<add>&#63;</add> the &#8220;Record&#8221; which<lb/> surely you will not feign to notice.  What else but&#8212;<lb/> the qualification of a little low chatham is <add>&#63;</add> &#38; indecency&#44; can be extracted from such a source or</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>company&#63; Or&#44; who constituted a few chatham Is clothes<lb/> boys teachers in <placeName>Israel</placeName>&#63;  So the <persName>Revd. Mr. DeSolla</persName><lb/> is with you again&#44; pray O<add>&#63;</add> let him introduce<lb/> to your notice or community&#44; all the <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> in the <placeName>United States</placeName>&#44; or he will make a fine affair<lb/> of the congregation.  My respected friend <persName>Revd. L. M.<lb/> Isaacs</persName> informs me that <persName>Mr. De S</persName> wished to attach<lb/> <persName>Mr. Morais</persName> in the messenger&#44; but that he &#40;<persName>Mr I</persName>&#41; refused<lb/> to permit it.  No doubt it will be &#8220;recorded&#8221; in the<lb/> <placeName>Chatham St.</placeName> gazette.  Now Revd. &#38; Dear Sir&#44; I have<lb/> an important congregational matter on hand&#44; you<lb/> must therefore pardon my brevity &#38; scrawl&#44; which I<lb/> feel ashamed to send by the side of that of my superior.<lb/>  However as he promises me his assistance I may<lb/> yet hope to some day climb the ladder<lb/> in the hope<lb/> that you are in perfect health.  With most sincere<lb/> wishes to your prosperity&#44; I now with very best regards</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)">Subscribe myself</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)">Most Sincerely Yours</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)"><persName role="author">M. O. I. Myers</persName></p>
				<p><addressee>Revd. I Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Please let me have as <hi rend="underline">early</hi> as<lb/> <hi rend="underline">possible</hi> 10 copies of your <add>Hebrew</add> Heb Primer No 1<lb/> and if obtainable a copy of work called <add>Hebrew</add> published in <placeName>Amsterdam</placeName> in <date>5528</date></p>
		</body>
